Michigan's Muslims are thinking globally, but running and voting locally
SavedRead AloudShare
Print
This is a photograph of a woman wearing a hijab standing outside.
Image 1. Machhadie Assi in Dearborn, Michigan, in September 2020. Assi is a Lebanese immigrant in the Dearborn area who has been politically active in her community for years. Photo: Emily Elconin/The Los Angeles Times
By Los Angeles Times, adapted by Newsela staff
Published:05/10/2021
Word Count:731
Editor's Note: The following article is from September 8, 2020. This was two months before the 2020 presidential election. The election was between Joseph Biden and Donald Trump.

More young Muslim Americans are excited about voting. Muslims are people who follow the religion of Islam. These young people are getting involved in elections.

Machhadie Assi is an immigrant from Lebanon. It is a small Middle Eastern country. In 2019, Assi met with voters in her community. She helped three elderly women register to vote.

Assi said 2016 was an important year. That year, former President Donald Trump made an order. The order targeted Muslim immigrants.

The order first called out seven countries. The countries were Iran, Iraq, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria, and Yemen. All of these countries had large Muslim populations. These countries were in the Middle East and North Africa region. The Islamic religion began around this region. But only about 1 out of 5 Muslims in the world live there.

The first two versions of the order were struck down by federal courts. A third version was approved by the Supreme Court. They upheld the order in June 2018.

President Joe Biden reversed the order on January 20, 2021. Since then, Muslims have been more politically active. They are voting more. Many are running for office.

This increasing activity is seen in Dearborn. It is a city in Michigan. It has one of the largest Arab American and Muslim communities in the country.

Dearborn Community Was Thriving
Arab immigrants arrived in Michigan in the late 1800s. Many found work in factories. Today, Dearborn has about 95,000 residents. About 43,500 of them claim Arab ancestry.

Not all Arab Americans are Muslim. However, most people in Dearborn are Muslim. Dearborn has one of the largest mosques in North America. It is the Islamic Center of America. A mosque is a place of worship for Muslims. This mosque serves the local Shiite community. Shiite and Sunnis make up the two main branches of Islam. Around the world, about 10 percent of the Muslim population is Shiite.

Photograph of a large mosque in Michigan.
Image 2. The Islamic Center of America is one of the largest mosques in the United States. It is located in Dearborn, Michigan. Photo: Dane Hillard/Wikimedia Commons

The Nation of Islam began in Michigan in 1930. This is a Black political and religious movement. But the majority of the Black Muslim population does not belong to the Nation of Islam. Muslims of African ancestry have been in North America for hundreds of years.

Dearborn's community has different cultural influences. Arabic and English are common languages. Arabic is the most common language in the Middle East. However, not everyone in the Middle East speaks Arabic.

Voters Look At All Issues
National issues are important to Arab American voters. One example is foreign policy. This is how the United States interacts with other countries. Local issues are also important. For example, air pollution is one concern. Poor air is connected to rising asthma rates in the Yemeni community. Asthma is a condition that makes it hard to breathe.

Muslim American organizations are doing important work. These groups are connecting with their Arab American voters. They are educating voters on the issues. They can help people register to vote.

This is a photo of Rashida Tlaib, a U.S. Representative.Zoom-in
Image 3. In 2018, Rashida Tlaib was elected to represent Michigan's 13th district in the U.S. House of Representatives. She was the first Muslim woman in the Michigan legislature and then became one of the first two Muslim women in Congress. Photo: United States Congress/Wikimedia Commons

Time To Be Heard By Voting
On September 11, 2001, the United States was attacked. This is known as 9/11. The attackers were from the Middle East. After 9/11, untrue rumors spread about Muslim Americans, people of Middle Eastern ancestry and Sikhs. These groups became targets of discrimination.

In 2016, Abdullah Hammoud won a state election in Michigan. He became a representative in the state's House of Representatives. Hammoud was the first Arab American Muslim to represent Dearborn's 15th District.

In 2018, more Arab American and Muslim voters turned out. Rashida Tlaib was elected to Congress. She is the daughter of Palestinian immigrants. Tlaib is also from Detroit.

Hammoud believes Muslim Americans helped him to win. It is important for them to see more Muslims take part in politics. They are helping to run the country. Their voices are being heard.


