By Associated Press, adapted by Newsela staff
Published:05/13/2021
Word Count:325
The COVID-19 pandemic has hurt families. The illness has been spreading everywhere. Some businesses have closed to try to stop the spread. Many people are not working right now. They have little money. They cannot buy food for their families.

Dylan Pfeifer wants to help families.  He is 8 years old. He lives in Arizona. He wants to make sure families have food to eat. So he holds food drives. He has collected more than 1,000 cans and boxes. People have given him money, too.  He has raised more than $900!

boy helps to lift a big boxZoom-out
Image 2. Dylan uses a lift to move a box filled with donated canned and boxed foods. The box safely stores the items until they are given to St. Mary's Food Bank. Photo: Cheyanne Mumphrey/AP

Dylan gives the money and food to a food bank. The one near him is St. Mary's Food Bank. It stores food. Then it gives food out to people for free.

Mom Says Nothing Can Stop Him
Dylan has held three food drives. Each one takes a lot of work. Dylan makes posters. He hands out flyers to people. His mother helps him. They put the information about the food drives on the internet.

boy with cans in his houseZoom-out
Image 3. Dylan sits with all the donations he received during his first food drive. Photo: Cheyanne Mumphrey/AP

He likes doing food drives. He said he wishes he could do a food drive every day.

Jerry Brown works with St. Mary's Food Bank. He said Dylan is brave. Dylan saw a problem in his community. He did something about it.

Erin Pfeifer is his mother. She said he keeps going. Nothing can stop him, she said.

boy puts a bag of peas in bagZoom-out
Image 4: Dylan volunteered with his mom at St. Mary's Food Bank in Phoenix on March 18, 2021. Photo: Cheyanne Mumphrey/AP

Dylan said he just wants to help the community.

He has advice for other kids who want to start a food drive. "Just do it!" he said.

