Kids aged 12 and up can now get a COVID-19 vaccine
SavedRead AloudShare
Print
A photo of a pair of blue gloves holding a Covid-19 vaccine. A young girl sits in the background, waiting to receive the vaccine.
Image 1. Getting vaccinated adds another layer of defense against the coronavirus. Photo: Images By Tang Ming Tung/Getty Images
By Newsela staff
Published:05/13/2021
Word Count:486
Some kids can now get the COVID-19 vaccine. It is approved for those 12 or older.

A vaccine is often a shot. It helps keep the body safe from viruses. The COVID-19 illness happens because of a virus. Vaccines give you immunity. This means your body can fight off an illness. This is just one way to get immunity. You can also get it from having the illness.

Getting Approval
The U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved the vaccine. It is part of the U.S. federal government. The FDA approves new drugs. It makes sure that food and drugs are safe.

Companies that make medicines run tests. They see how well a drug or vaccine works. They then give this information to the FDA. (You can learn more here.)

The vaccine was first tested in adults. The next vaccine tests were in teenagers. Now, children under 12 are getting tested.

The FDA approved a vaccine for teens on May 10th. The vaccine was made by Pfizer. On May 12th, another group looked at the FDA's approval. It was the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). It works to prevent and fight disease. The CDC also voted to allow teens to get the vaccine.

Some states started giving the vaccine after the FDA said it was okay. Other states were waiting for the CDC. Soon, anyone 12 or older can get the vaccine in more states.

Why Get Vaccinated?
COVID-19 has many symptoms. Some are: a fever, runny nose, cough and loss of taste or smell. Some children have few symptoms. Others have more. Getting a vaccine helps keep you from getting sick. It helps to keep the people around you safe.

A graphic showing how an mRNA vaccine works. Starting from top left, going counterclockwise, mRNA is injected. MRNA strands flow into cells which produce viral proteins. The viral proteins are detected by another cell. The cell produces antibodies. Antibodies attach to virusZoom-in
Image 2. Moderna and Pfizer's vaccines can help prevent COVID-19 infection in adults. The illustration shows how the vaccines work. Graphic: Newsela staff

Scientists and doctors want many people to get the vaccine. They want them to have immunity. The more people who have immunity, the less the virus spreads. This is known as herd immunity.

Scheduling A COVID-19 Shot
You may need an appointment. Your parent or caregiver can help you make one. Each state has its own way of giving out vaccines. Check the website for your state. The vaccine is free.

The Pfizer vaccine is two shots. You will need two visits. They will be about a month apart. You will get one shot at each visit. After you get your shot, you might feel side effects. Your arm might hurt a little. You might have a fever. These feelings should go away. If they do not, have your parents or caregiver call your doctor.

Vaccinated In Time For School This Fall?
Many students have been learning from home. This has been hard. A lot needs to happen to go back to school. Keeping more people safe from COVID-19 is the first step. Vaccines can help.

